;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 2: The Story Tree

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      2
  :title               "The Story Tree"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :draws-from-preserved (:book "book-of-games-preserved" :ch 1 :ch 2)
  :prose
"In chapter 1 each scene was a function that called the next scene by
name. That is fine for six scenes. For sixty it is a jungle of
functions. You can no longer see the shape of the story because it is
scattered across the code. The writer in you cannot see the game the
programmer in you is writing.

The fix is to move the story out of code and into data. A story becomes
a list of nodes; each node has an id, a text, and a list of choices.
The engine is one small function that reads the current node, paints its
text, waits for a choice, and jumps to whichever node the choice points
at. Now the story is a diagram you could sketch on a napkin. The engine
is 25 lines you write once and never think about again.

This is the physics of story-space: nodes are places, choices are edges,
a playthrough is a path through the graph. Once you see stories that way
you can design bigger ones.

---

## 2.1 A story as a list

Here is our kitchen story, but as data.

```scheme
(define story
  '((:id kitchen
     :text \"You are in a small kitchen. A red door to the north, a\n         blue door to the west.\"
     :choices ((:label \"go north (red)\" :goto garden)
               (:label \"go west (blue)\" :goto hallway)))
    (:id garden
     :text \"Bees. Tomatoes. A watering can that has been left out in\n         the rain and rusted through.\"
     :choices ((:label \"back to the kitchen\" :goto kitchen)
               (:label \"pick a tomato\"       :goto pocket-tomato)))
    (:id hallway
     :text \"Dust. A cat on the third step of a staircase. It watches\n         you without blinking.\"
     :choices ((:label \"upstairs\"           :goto upstairs)
               (:label \"back to the kitchen\" :goto kitchen)))
    (:id pocket-tomato
     :text \"You pocket a tomato. It leaves a warm wet spot on your\n         shirt. You feel obscurely happy.\"
     :choices ((:label \"back to the garden\" :goto garden)))
    (:id upstairs
     :text \"A small landing. The cat did not follow. A window is\n         open. There is a note on the sill in a hand you know.\"
     :choices ((:label \"read the note\"      :goto the-note)
               (:label \"go back down\"       :goto hallway)))
    (:id the-note
     :text \"The note says: 'I am at the beehive. Do not worry about\n         the honey. I will be back before you get bored.'\"
     :choices ((:label \"end for today\"      :goto ending)))
    (:id ending
     :text \"You put the note in your pocket, next to the tomato. You\n         decide to go to the hive.\"
     :choices ())))
```

Six scenes. Two endings (the ending node, and the pocket-tomato node
which loops but does not advance). Every scene has an id, a text, and
zero or more choices. Each choice has a label the kid sees and a goto
that names the next node. That is the whole vocabulary of a story tree.

The story is now a diagram you could draw on paper. Kitchen at the top.
Garden left, hallway right. Garden has pocket-tomato hanging off it.
Hallway has upstairs above it. Upstairs has the-note, which has ending.
That is the shape. Anyone who reads the data can see the shape. Compare
to chapter 1 where the shape was smeared across seven function
definitions — you could not see it without running the game.

---

## 2.2 The engine that walks the tree

We need one function that takes a story and a starting id and does the
right thing. Here is the whole engine.

```scheme
;; Find a node in the story by id.
(define (node-lookup story id)
  (find (lambda (n) (eq? (node-get n :id) id)) story))

(define (node-get node key)
  (cond ((null? node) #f)
        ((eq? (car node) key) (cadr node))
        (else (node-get (cddr node) key))))

;; Paint a node and let the kid choose.
(define (play-node story id)
  (let ((node (node-lookup story id)))
    (if (not node)
        (paint-text 20 40 (string-append \"?? node not found: \" (symbol->string id)))
        (begin
          (scene/imagine)
          (surface/paper)
          (paint-text 20 40 (node-get node :text))
          (paint-choices (node-get node :choices) 20 160)
          (on-key
            (lambda (k)
              (let ((chosen (choice-for-key (node-get node :choices) k)))
                (if chosen
                    (play-node story (node-get chosen :goto))
                    (play-node story id)))))))))

(define (paint-choices choices y0 x)
  (let loop ((cs choices) (i 0))
    (when (not (null? cs))
      (paint-text x (+ y0 (* i 25))
        (string-append \"[\" (number->letter (+ i 1)) \"] \"
                       (node-get (car cs) :label)))
      (loop (cdr cs) (+ i 1)))))

(define (choice-for-key choices k)
  (let ((idx (letter->index k)))
    (if (and (>= idx 0) (< idx (length choices)))
        (list-ref choices idx)
        #f)))

(define (number->letter n)
  (list-ref '(A B C D E F G H) (- n 1)))

(define (letter->index k)
  (case k
    ((a) 0) ((b) 1) ((c) 2) ((d) 3)
    ((e) 4) ((f) 5) ((g) 6) ((h) 7)
    (else -1)))

;; Kick it off.
(big-bang :init (lambda () (play-node story 'kitchen)))
```

Twenty-five lines of engine, plus five of helpers. It never mentions
kitchens, doors, or gardens. It works for any story you write in the
same shape. This is the point of pulling data out of code: the engine
gets reused; the story gets rewritten as often as you like.

Change the story and the engine still works. Add ten more scenes to
`story` and press play again. That is a design win worth pausing on.
Anytime you catch yourself writing the same shape three times in a row,
that shape belongs in data.

---

## 2.3 Marking visited nodes

A kid plays a small tree twice and the second time she should see which
choices she has already tried. We use Cortex to track it.

```scheme
;; Track visited nodes across sessions.
(define (play-node-remembering story id)
  (cortex/write 'last-node id)
  (let* ((visited (or (cortex/read 'visited-nodes) '()))
         (already (member id visited)))
    (cortex/write 'visited-nodes (cons id visited))
    (let ((node (node-lookup story id)))
      (scene/imagine)
      (surface/paper)
      (paint-text 20 40 (node-get node :text))
      (paint-choices-with-visited
        (node-get node :choices) visited 20 160)
      (on-key
        (lambda (k)
          (let ((chosen (choice-for-key (node-get node :choices) k)))
            (if chosen
                (play-node-remembering story (node-get chosen :goto))
                (play-node-remembering story id))))))))

(define (paint-choices-with-visited choices visited x y0)
  (let loop ((cs choices) (i 0))
    (when (not (null? cs))
      (let* ((c (car cs))
             (target (node-get c :goto))
             (seen? (member target visited))
             (label (string-append \"[\" (number->letter (+ i 1)) \"] \"
                                   (node-get c :label)
                                   (if seen? \" (visited)\" \"\"))))
        (paint-text x (+ y0 (* i 25)) label))
      (loop (cdr cs) (+ i 1)))))
```

Now when the kid opens the game tomorrow, the choices she has already
tried are marked with 'visited.' Not disabled — she can still take them,
maybe she wants to revisit — but tagged. She has a sense of the shape
of the space she has already explored. That is a small piece of respect
for her time.

`cortex/read` returns `#f` if the key has never been set. We
`(or ... '())` to default to the empty list. Then `member` checks if a
node id is in the list. `member` returns a tail-list if found, `#f` if
not, which is truthy/falsy — perfect for `if`.

---

## 2.4 Endings and dead ends

An ending is any node whose choices list is empty. The engine should
notice this and offer the kid a way to reset or replay.

```scheme
(define (play-node-with-endings story id)
  (let ((node (node-lookup story id)))
    (scene/imagine)
    (surface/paper)
    (paint-text 20 40 (node-get node :text))
    (let ((choices (node-get node :choices)))
      (if (null? choices)
          (paint-ending-panel)
          (paint-choices choices 20 160))
      (on-key
        (lambda (k)
          (if (null? choices)
              (case k
                ((r) (play-node-with-endings story 'kitchen))   ;; replay
                ((q) (return-to-menu))
                (else (play-node-with-endings story id)))
              (let ((chosen (choice-for-key choices k)))
                (if chosen
                    (play-node-with-endings story (node-get chosen :goto))
                    (play-node-with-endings story id)))))))))

(define (paint-ending-panel)
  (paint-text 20 220 \"~~~ end ~~~\")
  (paint-text 20 260 \"[R] replay from start   [Q] back to menu\"))
```

The kid reaches the ending scene. The engine sees the empty choices
list and paints the ending panel instead. R starts over from the
kitchen. Q returns to whatever menu wraps the game. An ending is not the
end of the code; it is the end of THIS playthrough. Kids should always
have a way back to the beginning.

---

## 2.5 Multiple endings

A tree with multiple endings feels bigger than it is. Ten scenes with
three endings feels like a real story; ten scenes with one ending feels
like a hallway.

Rewrite the story to have three endings — the beehive, the cat's
staircase, and the rusted watering can.

```scheme
(define story-with-endings
  '((:id kitchen
     :text \"A small kitchen. Red door north. Blue door west.\"
     :choices ((:label \"north\" :goto garden)
               (:label \"west\"  :goto hallway)))
    (:id garden
     :text \"Bees. Tomatoes. A watering can rusted through.\"
     :choices ((:label \"back\"                :goto kitchen)
               (:label \"study the can\"       :goto ending-watering-can)))
    (:id hallway
     :text \"Cat on the stairs. Watches you.\"
     :choices ((:label \"upstairs\"            :goto upstairs)
               (:label \"back\"                 :goto kitchen)
               (:label \"sit with the cat\"    :goto ending-cat)))
    (:id upstairs
     :text \"A note on the sill. It mentions the hive.\"
     :choices ((:label \"go to the hive\"      :goto ending-hive)
               (:label \"back\"                 :goto hallway)))
    (:id ending-watering-can
     :text \"You realize the can is your grandmother's. You keep it.\"
     :choices ())
    (:id ending-cat
     :text \"You sit for a long time. The cat allows itself to be pet.\"
     :choices ())
    (:id ending-hive
     :text \"You find the hive. There is honey. There is a friend.\"
     :choices ())))
```

Six scenes, three endings. The kid can replay and get a different
outcome each time. She will not replay unless the first ending felt
weighted enough to make her curious about the others. That is a lesson
for chapter 11 — branches only matter if the endings matter. Do not
make three endings just to have three; make three endings if you know
which one you want the kid to reach first.

---

## 2.6 A worked scene: what the tree feels like when it is small

Here is a five-node story called 'The Return.' A person walks home to
a place she has not been in years. Three endings.

```scheme
(define the-return
  '((:id door
     :text \"You are standing on the porch of a house you have not\n         been to in twelve years. The key still works.\"
     :choices ((:label \"unlock and walk in\"       :goto foyer)
               (:label \"ring the bell instead\"   :goto bell)
               (:label \"turn around and leave\"   :goto ending-leave)))
    (:id foyer
     :text \"It smells like your mother. Nobody is home. The kitchen\n         light is on.\"
     :choices ((:label \"kitchen\"                 :goto kitchen)
               (:label \"upstairs, your old room\" :goto old-room)))
    (:id bell
     :text \"A woman you have not seen in twelve years opens the door.\n         She is smaller than you remembered.\"
     :choices ((:label \"tell her you came\"     :goto ending-reunion)
               (:label \"apologize for the years\" :goto ending-apology)))
    (:id kitchen
     :text \"A note on the fridge in her handwriting. 'If you come\n         home, there is soup on the stove.'\"
     :choices ((:label \"eat the soup\"           :goto ending-soup)))
    (:id old-room
     :text \"The bed is made. Your books are on the shelf, dusted.\n         She kept it.\"
     :choices ((:label \"lie down\"                :goto ending-soup)))
    (:id ending-leave  :text \"You do not go in. That is a decision.\" :choices ())
    (:id ending-reunion :text \"You cry. So does she. It is not fixed. It is started.\" :choices ())
    (:id ending-apology :text \"'I know,' she says. That is all.\" :choices ())
    (:id ending-soup    :text \"The soup is still warm. She knew you were coming.\" :choices ())))
```

Twelve years is specific. 'Smaller than you remembered' is honest. Soup
still warm is a lie the kid can catch — did she know, or did the soup
just happen to be warm? The kid decides. That is what a story tree gives
you room for.

Notice that 'leave' is one of the endings. Sometimes not going in IS
the choice. Do not always force the kid down the story. Let refusal be
a real option. This is a lesson about consent as design: a game that
punishes the kid for opting out is a game that lies about its choices.

---

## 2.7 Common desktop tasks — an operator's return-policy tree

A shopkeeper has a return policy. She could write it as three
paragraphs of legalese or she could write it as a five-scene story tree.
The kid — I mean, the customer — walks through the tree, and by the end
they know exactly what applies to their situation.

```scheme
(define return-policy-tree
  '((:id start
     :text \"How can I help? Did the piece arrive broken, was it not\n         what you expected, or has it been over 30 days?\"
     :choices ((:label \"arrived broken\"   :goto broken)
               (:label \"not what expected\" :goto not-expected)
               (:label \"over 30 days\"      :goto over-thirty)))
    (:id broken
     :text \"I am sorry. That is on me. Send a photo of the damage\n         and I will make it right same day.\"
     :choices ((:label \"got it, thank you\" :goto ending-broken-yes)))
    (:id not-expected
     :text \"Return for full refund within 14 days. You cover ship.\n         I will refund immediately on receipt — no waiting.\"
     :choices ((:label \"start the return\"  :goto ending-not-expected)))
    (:id over-thirty
     :text \"After 30 days it depends on the piece. If it broke of its\n         own accord, I usually cover 50%. Tell me what happened?\"
     :choices ((:label \"broke on its own\"     :goto ending-repair)
               (:label \"I dropped it\"          :goto ending-drop)))
    (:id ending-broken-yes    :text \"Photo tool below. I will reply within the hour.\" :choices ())
    (:id ending-not-expected  :text \"Return-label form below. Thank you for being kind about it.\" :choices ())
    (:id ending-repair        :text \"Send a photo. I will quote 50%-off repair or replace.\" :choices ())
    (:id ending-drop          :text \"Best I can do is a repair quote. No refund past 30.\" :choices ())))
```

The customer walks through the tree in fifteen seconds. She feels heard.
She has been offered a specific action. She has a real answer, not a
paragraph of maybe. That is what narrative shape does for a shopkeeper
who does not want to write help-center documentation and does want to
treat customers like people.

The shopkeeper wrote each ending in her own voice ('that is on me,'
'no waiting'). If she gave the tree to the runtime and asked for wording
suggestions, the runtime would tune it — but the shape and the values are
the shopkeeper's.

---

## 2.8 Routing patterns for trees

Three shapes worth knowing when you design a tree:

**The lattice.** Some choices lead to the same later node from different
directions. Kitchen and garden both loop back; a save room is reachable
from three floors. Trees with lattices feel richer because the kid can
approach the same scene with different history. Cortex makes this
delicious in chapter 3.

**The gate.** A node the kid cannot reach without a specific past
choice. 'You cannot go through the door unless you took the key' is
implemented by checking Cortex before offering the door. Chapter 8 does
this properly with inventory. For now, just know that a tree with gates
feels more like a world and less like a menu.

**The pruned branch.** Some choices should disappear based on what the
kid has done. If you gave the honey to the bees in scene 2, you cannot
also eat it in scene 5. Filter the choices list before painting it.
This is where `filter` earns its place in your toolkit.

```scheme
(define (available-choices node)
  (filter
    (lambda (c)
      (let ((req (node-get c :requires)))
        (if req
            (cortex/read req)         ;; only if the flag is set
            #t)))                     ;; unconditional
    (node-get node :choices)))
```

Choices with `:requires 'have-lantern` only appear if `(cortex/read
'have-lantern)` is truthy. Choices with no `:requires` always appear.
Ten lines, and now your trees have conditional edges.

---

## 2.9 Closing

You have replaced code with data. Six scenes now take up eight lines of
list; the engine reads them and does the right thing. You can add
scenes without touching the engine. You can share the story with a
friend and she can rewrite the words without touching Scheme at all.

Try this: write a five-scene story about something that happened to you
this week. It does not have to be interesting to anyone else. It has to
have three choices somewhere and two endings. Load it into the engine
you built. Play it. If your friend plays it and asks 'wait, what did
this really mean?' — you have made a small narrative game.

Chapter 3 is about memory. The story tree walks itself; Cortex
remembers what it walked. When the shopkeeper says 'I heard you came
through the red door,' it is Cortex whispering to her. That is where
narrative games start to feel alive.")
